{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20909"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11803"},{"type":"tags","id":"11804"},{"type":"tags","id":"12381"},{"type":"tags","id":"12769"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33236"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the principle of Sanger sequencing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Digestion of PCR products with restriction enzymes to identify mutations","Simultaneous amplification of multiple genomic regions","Generation of DNA fragments of all possible lengths with fluorescent terminators","Monitoring DNA amplification in real-time using fluorophore indicators","Detection of mutations at a single nucleotide position using primer extension"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration of DNA fragments of all possible lengths with fluorescent terminators\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes Sanger sequencing. In this method, a PCR product is mixed with DNA polymerase, a specific primer, regular nucleotides, and four di-deoxy terminator nucleotides (A, T, G, and C) labeled with different fluorescent tags. The reaction produces DNA fragments of all possible lengths, each ending with a fluorescently labeled base. After size separation by electrophoresis, the sequence can be read and compared with the normal sequence to detect mutations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigestion of PCR products with restriction enzymes to identify mutations\u003C/strong\u003E describes restriction fragment length analysis, which takes advantage of restriction enzymes that cut DNA at specific sequences. This approach is useful when a mutation affects a restriction site.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous amplification of multiple genomic regions\u003C/strong\u003E describes the initial step of Next-Generation Sequencing (NGS), where primers for many different genomic regions are used simultaneously. NGS is more sensitive than Sanger sequencing and can identify mutations present in only a small percentage of cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitoring DNA amplification in real-time using fluorophore indicators\u003C/strong\u003E describes real-time PCR, which uses fluorophore indicators to detect and quantify particular nucleic acid sequences during the exponential phase of DNA amplification rather than after PCR is complete.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of mutations at a single nucleotide position using primer extension\u003C/strong\u003E describes single-base primer extension, where a primer hybridizes one base upstream of the target position, and differently colored terminator fluorescent nucleotides are added. This technique is very sensitive but only produces one base pair of sequence data.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESanger sequencing has been a fundamental technique in molecular diagnostics for decades, allowing for the detection of mutations by direct comparison of the obtained sequence with the normal reference sequence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sanger sequencing uses dideoxynucleotide chain terminators with fluorescent labels to generate DNA fragments of varying lengths that can be separated by size.","The pattern of fluorescent fragments in Sanger sequencing allows the DNA sequence to be read directly from shortest to longest fragment.","Sanger sequencing remains an important method for detecting mutations by comparing the obtained sequence with a reference sequence.","Next-generation sequencing (NGS) offers higher throughput than Sanger sequencing by simultaneously sequencing millions of DNA fragments.","Different DNA sequencing methods have specific applications based on their sensitivity, throughput, and ability to detect various types of mutations."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 181-182"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79562"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T18:21:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T19:00:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"9694